inline_comments.message:
Note the output from running the following class:

============================================================
public class Junk
{
  static String str1 = initString("Initializing 'str1'");
  static String str2;
  static
  {
	str2 = "Initializing 'str2'";
	System.out.println(str2);
  }
  static String str3 = initString("Initializing 'str3'");

  private static String initString(String value)
  {
	System.out.println(value);
	return(value);
  }

  static public void main(String args[])
  {
	System.out.println("Running 'main'");
  }
}
============================================================
$ java Junk
Initializing 'str1'
Initializing 'str2'
Initializing 'str3'
Running 'main'
============================================================

Note that 'str2', is initialized after 'str1', even though 'str1' initialization is through a method, and 'str2' using a static block. Java does try to initialize dependencies before dependents, but I don't know if that always works as expected, particularly when there is the possibility of a dependency loop between classes.

I think it is all ok as it is.  There is only one single call to initLogger() now, all other ones have been removed including the shared static data in this class.

Check this out: 

https://stackoverflow.com/questions/32976943/java-static-initialization-thread-safety-guarantee-in-language-spec 

and the reference to the section in the Java Language Specification that details the synchronized static initialization.

I also corroborated it with this little multithreaded test program:

jh1730@newton:~/dev/open/LF/tmp$ cat StaticTest.java
import java.util.Date;

public class StaticTest {

  public static volatile int count = 0;

  static {
    count("start-static-block", count);
    System.out.println(".... start 30 sec. sleep within static block ..");
    try {Thread.sleep(30000);} catch(Exception e) {e.printStackTrace();}
    System.out.println(".... end 30 sec. sleep within static block ..");
    count("end-static-block", 1);
  }

  public StaticTest() {
	count("constructor",999);
  }

  public static void count(String m, int c) {
    count=c;
    System.out.println(new Date() + ": " + m + " count=" + count);
  }
}
